Terra Invicta Tools

A series of Python scripts for decoding and analyzing the data files from Pavonis Interactive's hybrid strategy game,
"Terra Invicta"

This project was originally started as a way for me to quickly calculate the total cost for the large number of
researchable in-game technologies. It rapidly expanded to cover most of the modules, projects, and various other
in-game concepts.

The various data files packaged with the game are scattered and rather hard to navigate just through regular
text editors. So these scripts read and pack the data into easily queried relational records. This allows a wide
array of operations to be performed on the data.


Demonstrating these scripts:
    - First, ensure that the latest version of Python 3 is installed on your machine, and the binary present in the users PATH
      This will allow you to run the commands with "./command.py" instead of having to do "python3 command.py"

    - Run "init.py" command found at the top-level, this will initialize the database.
      Make sure it follows: './init.py tidb.sql' to initialize with the provided schema.
      This will create a file called "dbout.db", which is the default name for our database file.

    - Once the database is successfully initialized,run the "load.py" command, this will load the data into the database
      Use the following: './load.py dbout.db testfiles', this will load the .json files under "testfiles" into the database

    - Once the database has been fully loaded, you may now run the "poke.py" command to perform various operations on the data.
      "poke.py" has a number of subcommands.
      The "list" commands follow the form: "./poke.py list-X [database-file]"
      the "show" commands follow the form: "./poke.py show-X [database-file] [identifier]"

    Examples of this command:

        - './poke.py list-modules dbout.db' shows all of the modules in the database
        - './poke.py show-module dbout.db MODULE_NAME' shows the details of a given module
        - './poke.py show-module --csv dbout.db MODULE_NAME' shows the details formatted as CSV
        - './poke.py show-module --json dbout.db MODULE_NAME' shows the details formatted as JSON
        - './poke.py list-projects dbout.db' list all of the projects in the database
        - './poke.py list-projects --truncate dbout.db' list all of the projects in the database, truncating to just the name
        - './poke.py show-tech dbout.db TECH_OR_PROJECT' list the details of a given technology or project
        - './poke.py show-dependencies dbout.db TECH_OR_PROJECT' list all dependencies for a given technology or project
        - './poke.py show-tech-cost dbout.db TECH_OR_PROJECT' show the total cost of a technology or project, factoring in all dependencies

    I would recommend looking at the 'show-dependencies' subcommand, as it was the original purpose of this project
